  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3771736167" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3771736167" />
    <a title="Beenish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/106139933-beenish"><img alt="Beenish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616760756p2/106139933.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3771736167?book_show_action=true">Jan 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beenish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beenish" href="/user/show/106139933-beenish">Beenish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106139933-beenish?shelf=ya">ya</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106139933-beenish?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106139933-beenish?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106139933-beenish?shelf=laini-tailor">laini-tailor</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106139933-beenish?shelf=books-read-in-2021">books-read-in-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3771736167" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3688857327239591262">4.5★ | Just like any other author, <b>Laini Taylor</b> books are either for you or they&apos;re not. It&apos;s really amazing how a reader like me who loves fast paced books, loves whatever Laini Taylor writes—<i>aka such addictive and descriptive books.</i> I am so enthralled by the storyline and the concepts, the rich and vivid writing, and how from a book of <b>rainbows and sunshine,</b> it went on to be a book so <b>dark and heavy.</b><br/><br/>My reviews of<br/><a href='https://bit.ly/3bvKOr1' rel='nofollow noopener'>Daughter of Smoke and Bone</a> 3.99★<br/><a href='https://bit.ly/362Hpfu' rel='nofollow noopener'>Night of Cake &amp; Puppets</a> 5★<br/><a href='https://bit.ly/3o8yq2u' rel='nofollow noopener'>Dreams of Gods and Monst</a></span>
  <span id="freeText3688857327239591262" style="display:none">4.5★ | Just like any other author, <b>Laini Taylor</b> books are either for you or they're not. It's really amazing how a reader like me who loves fast paced books, loves whatever Laini Taylor writes—<i>aka such addictive and descriptive books.</i> I am so enthralled by the storyline and the concepts, the rich and vivid writing, and how from a book of <b>rainbows and sunshine,</b> it went on to be a book so <b>dark and heavy.</b><br><br>My reviews of<br><a href="https://bit.ly/3bvKOr1" rel="nofollow noopener">Daughter of Smoke and Bone</a> 3.99★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/362Hpfu" rel="nofollow noopener">Night of Cake &amp; Puppets</a> 5★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/3o8yq2u" rel="nofollow noopener">Dreams of Gods and Monsters</a> 3.5★<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>Once upon a time, an angel and a devil fell in love and dared to imagine a new way of living—one without massacres and torn throats and bonfires of the fallen, without revenants or bastard armies or children ripped from their mothers’ arms to take their turn in the killing and dying.<br>Once, the lovers lay entwined in the moon’s secret temple and dreamed of a world that was like a jewel box without a jewel—a paradise waiting for them to find it and fill it with their happiness.<br>This was not that world.</i>
</blockquote><br><br><b>
  <u>ABOUT THE BOOK</u>
</b><br>"<i>Days of Blood and Starlight</i>" turns every shining, bright, cheerful and peaceful aspect of "<i>Daughter of Smoke and Bone</i>" into a dark, chaotic book. Where the prequel focused on romance and mystery, this book continues to focus on <b>grief, revenge, lies, betrayal, manipulation and war. AND rape.</b> But even after all that, there's still <b>Hope</b> and a little trust, a little faith; a speck of light capable of piercing the dark shadow through which this book takes us. Everything is so serious and so brutal at times that it gave me shivers and even made me cry. I'm so thankful for <b>Zuze and Mik's</b> adorable chapters, coz otherwise idk if I'd even have been able to read it. <b>I know I've been praising Laini Taylor's writing a lot but seriously,</b> I must say she has a fantastic way of creating tension and making the readers feel the intensity of what is going on. <br><br><i>If you haven't read the prequel, don't read ahead to avoid <b>spoilers for that book.</b></i><br><br><b>
  <u>REVIEW</u>
</b><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>
    <i>
      <b>Once upon a time, an angel and a devil held a wishbone between them.<br>And it's snap split the world in two.</b>
    </i>
  </i>
</blockquote><br><br>After snapping the wishbone, Karou gets all her memories back from the time when her soul was in her real flesh. From the time she was Madrigal of the Kirin.<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1611285009ra/30736845.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“Let’s see. You know how, at the end of Romeo and Juliet, Juliet wakes up in the crypt and Romeo’s already dead? He thought she was dead so he killed himself right next to her?”<br>“Yeah. [•••]”<br>“Well, imagine if she woke up and he was still alive, but…But he had killed her whole family. And burned her city. And killed and enslaved her people.”</i>
</blockquote><br>—That's kind of what Akiva and Karou's story is like.<br><br>As soon as she remembers everything, she is filled with love and memory of a dream about a world remade and peace. BUT, Akiva doesn't like keeping things from her and so, he told her that he didn't know that she was alive, that he lost himself and there was only vengeance. But most of all, he told her that her chimaera family was no more. That was it. That was all it took Karou to hate him.<br><br><blockquote>[•••] <i>they had found each other, even across worlds and lifetimes. <b>For a pure and shining moment, Karou had known joy.<br>Which Akiva had ended</b> with those words, spoken in deepest shame, most wretched sorrow.<br>“They’re all dead.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>On one hand, Karou does not find it in herself to forgive Akiva. She takes Brimstone's job of being a resurrectionist and starts creating new and strong bodies for the souls of her (Chimaera) people.<br>And on the other hand, Akiva shares the burden of his secrets with his siblings, Hazael and Liraz, and refuses to kill another chimaera.<br>But, on both sides, there is corruption within the armies which makes way for <b>hope.</b><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>good and bad were words for a child’s primer, and did not come close to representing the magnitude of tragedy on the one hand, and on the other… hope.</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Ps: please read this book! There is a fantastic world to discover along with these beautiful characters.<br><br><b>
  <u>ABOUT THE CHARACTERS (no spoilers)</u>
</b><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“There’s no reason for you to believe it,” he said, “but I’m done killing chimaera.”<br>“You told me that once before.”<br>“It was true then,” he said. “And it’s true now.” After Bullfinch he had stopped killing chimaera.<br>And after her death, he had started again.</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Idk how you all feel about <b>Akiva,</b> I've read reviews where people say they just didn't care about him (or Karou) but I connected to him in a very emotional way. I could feel how curious he was, I could see how strongly he loved, I could understand how much he was burning with it and I felt really hurt for all the burden he was carrying. I was very very grateful to his siblings, <b>Liraz and Hazael</b> for being there for him and understanding him. We got a bit more of both of them and I absolutely love them. I loved <b>Liraz's</b> nature, acting like a stone-hearted person but fiercely loving her brothers deep in her heart. I loved <b>Hazael's</b> calm presence and light humour. I just loved seeing how they both come to see things the way Akiva did and realized how important that was.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>she had been Madrigal of the Kirin, who loved an angel and died for it. But she wasn’t Madrigal anymore, or chimaera. She was Karou. Human.<br>Sort of.</i>
</blockquote><br><br><b>Karou</b> went under some serious character development in my opinion even if it wasn't much, it was really good. I loved seeing her vulnerability and her strength. I loved her way of processing things and emotions <b>BUT</b> I didn't like her surrender. Still, it's just one thing and we all make mistakes, so that's okay but it bothered me coz it didn't get along with her character esp when she was making such smart moves. I loved how she stood up "you-know-who" but I didn't like the way she was hurting <b>Akiva</b> and at the same time I was trying to understand what she's going through and omg! I just went through SO MANY EMOTIONS.<br><br>There are more characters that I absolutely loved seeing like all the cute <b>Zuze and Mik scenes</b> but there are also a few characters who were there but I didn't get the point of them, so maybe they'll appear in the next book? Anyways, that's all I want to say without spoiling :)<br><br><b>
  <u>My Thoughts/Opinions</u>
</b><br>This book really got me hooked. I'm surprised by how Laini Taylor created a world of equal beauty and horror.<br><br><b>One thing, I struggled with during the first book</b> was the Angels. I knew it was all about good and evil but even though the chimaera were explained in detail, there wasn't much about Angels. This book, however, clarified that for me and having read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3438652105" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <b>Strange the Dreamer</b>
</a> (<i>which, if you haven't read, I'd suggest please do.</i>), I was amazed at how differently Laini Taylor uses the concept of <b>Gods and Monsters</b> in both books. Both are unique ❤️<br>And <b>the thing that troubled me a teeny-tiny bit</b> in this book was how quickly the narrative changed from one character to another. It's why I cut a point 5 star. Over all, this book is beautiful and a bit too emotional to have made me cry. I loved it from the start to the last lines. I was not bored for a single moment though I understand some people do because for them, the book is slow. It IS slow but in a good way ;)<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1611285009i/30736846._SY540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>By numbersandheroes | deviantart.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3688857327239591262" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


